    "text": "Erdős Problem #91: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Suppose $A\\subset \\mathbb{R}^2$ has $\\lvert A\\rvert=n$ and minimises the number of distinct distances between points in $A$. Prove that for large $n$ there are at least two (and probably many) such $A$ which are non-similar. Current best: In \\cite{Er87b} Erd\\H{o}s says that there are at least two non-similar examples for $6\\leq n\\leq 9$. Prize: no. OEIS: A186704. Tags: distances, geometry.",
